<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Johnston, John. Description of the Country around Lakes Superior and Huron, 1809. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0018</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">it is oval, and when Ripe a dark blue, and sometimes black; the seed is an agreeable bitter, as is that of the bush cranberry<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Hazel is here quite a Shrub but produces in good Seasons a Vast quantity of excellent nuts<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The velvet leaved tea is found in abundance on the borders of marshes it grows about two feet high and has its narrow pointed leaves scattered half way up the Stem but producing a flower Shaped bunch at the top, the leaf is a Sea green the under part of which is a brownish Yellow Which feels like Velvet it is a Strong bitter but when made use of as tea is not disagreeable and is Said to be good for weak nerves<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The sand cherry has much the appearance of the black willow both as to the bark and leaf; it seldom exceeds two feet in heighth, Where it spreads out its branches horizontally the fruit is much Richer and Sweeter than on those that are perpendicular<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  It is never found in perfection but on the dryest lands<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The fruit when Ripe, <span class="DelHand-author">a</span><span class="AddHand-author">i</span>s the most perfect black, the stone also resembles that of other cherries when bruised along with the fruit it makes an excellent Liquor<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The fruit has a certain bitterness and is very astringent<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The Indians and French eat them, as they do everything else that is <span class="DelHand-author">stale</span> <span class="AddHand-author">in the least</span> agreeable to excess, without any bad effects Resulting from it: But the fact is</p>

